did.abstract: Manuscript copies of documents in the Bibliothèque Nationale, the Archives Nationales and other archival sources in France, almost all relating to religious questions in the Languedoc region. The copies, which were made at the turn of the century, are contained in 373 volumes. Two collections from the Bibliothèque Nationale make up the major portion of the collection: The Collection de Languedoc (48 v.).

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Cabié Collection (MS 122). Manuscripts and Archives, Yale University Library.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Scholar; Studied at the Polytechnique in 1865, but did not complete his work there. Returned to the Languedoc region and devoted his time toward editing texts, and studying prehistoric history and archaeology. A major work by Cabié was Guerres de religion dans le sud-est de la France, 1906.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Cabié Collection consists of a number (380 vol.) of copies of manuscripts which were made at the turn of the century by E. Cabié and others. The copies are hand-written and usually clearly legible; the collection is in good state of repair; the paper is not brittle and the volumes are well bound.

The purpose of Cabié's work was to collect as much material as possible about the Languedoc (which he defines as the area west of the Rhône, south of the Tarn and north of the Pyrénées). Cabié thus went through theBibliothèque Nationaleand theArchives Nationales, selecting those manuscripts which pertained to his field and had them copied.
The Cabié Collection and the Bénédicitins Collection.

The Doat Collection. The Doat Collection consists of copies made by M. Doat, President of the Chambre des Comptes de Naverre, and others, under Colbert's orders. The purpose of this endeavor was to give Colbert an idea of the extent and nature of royal privileges in the Languedoc. The collection thus consists exclusively of copies of manuscripts which Doat made in the Languedocian archives; publics, municipal, and monastical. Doat's survey, according to Cabié, was exhaustive and the copies remarkably accurate.

These copies were filed by Doat as well as Cabié in two ways: 1) by subject of study: heretics (allegories, heresy), 28 volumes; Crusades, 4 volumes; French history, general and 2) by locality (and chronologically): Albi, 15 volumes; Rodez, 10 volumes; Foix, 30 volumes.
According to Cabié, the Doat Collection, as he copied it, is the richest collection available on the Languedoc. The material on Albi and the heresy is particularly extensive.

The Benedictins Collection was not copied in its entirety. Nonetheless, Cabié filled 40 volumes of his collection with this material. Benedictins refers to two Benedictine monks: Dom de Vic and Dom Vaissete, who lived during the XVIII century and who wrote theHistoire Générale du Languedoc. The Collection comprises their notes and materials: 1) notes: geographical notes refer to the XVIII th century and are filed by locality, 5 volumes and historical notes (1200-1600); also filed by locality, genealogical notes. 2) documents, 28 volumes of manuscripts, charters, letters. Filed chronologically (400?-1600). Senechaussé records for the Languedoc, filed by date (1272-1585).

The Boat and Benedictins Collections account for 220 out of 380 of Cabié's volumes. The remainder includes copies of choice of manuscripts found in the Bibliothèque Nationale. and the Archives Nationales. Cabié's arrangement of the copies is according to the Collection from which they were made:
1.) Fonds Latin (Biblioth. Nat.) 15 volumes concern early Languedoc history (7th-13th century). Emphasis is on religious matters.

2.) Fonds Francais (Biblioth. Nat.): 2 collections of 16th century correspondence, 5 volumes; 40 volumes of copies of manuscripts of the Trésor des Chartes (an XVIIIth century collection of copies and originals of manuscripts — a centralized general archive). Cabié selected the useful (i.e. Languedoc) materials and had them copied (1250-1500); and Serilly Collection (same structure as Doat.) Serilly was a colleague of Doat's), arranged chronogically.
3.) Baluze Collection. (Biblioth. Nat.) 3 volumes. Religious. (Languedoc)
4.) Moreau Collection. (Biblioth. Nat.) 2 vamps. Religious. (Biblioth. Nat.)
5.) Hozier Collection. 1 volums; list of nobles in Languedoc.
6.) Trésor des Chartes. (Archives Nationales.) Concerning the relationships of authority (royal privileges, relationships between local nobles.) 40 volumes, chronologically arranged (1250-1450).
7.) Monuments Historiques. (Archives Nationales.) 3 volumes. Sénéchauseé of Toulouse records, 14th century.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The materials are arranged in the following sections: Collection Doat (Bibliothèque Nationale), Collection du Languedoc (Bénédictins) (Bibliothèque nationale), Fonds Latin (Bibliothèque nationale), Fonds Français (Bibliothèque nationale), Collection Baluze (Bibliothèque nationale), Collection Moreau (Bibliothèque nationals), Hozier (Bibliothèque nationale), Trésor des Chartes (Archives nationales), and Monuments historiques (Archives nationales).

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: Copyright status for collection materials is unknown, though much of the material in this collection is likely in the public domain. Transmission or reproduction of materials protected by U.S. Copyright Law (Title 17, U.S.C.) beyond that allowed by fair use requires the written permission of the copyright owners. Works not in the public domain cannot be commercially exploited without permission of the copyright owners. Responsibility for any use rests exclusively with the user.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: The collection is open for research.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: [Made up chiefly of papers of the Bénédietins Dom.Vaissète (c.1684-1756) and Dom. De Vic (1670-1734), editors of the "Histoite générale de Languedoc", which appeared 1730-1745. The collection is described by Ph. Lauer in "Bibl.Nat.,Coll. Man. s. 1'hist. des prov. de Fr: inventaire", pp.xiii-xv, and 193-252; partially in the "Cabinet historique", II, 2e partie, and III, 2e partie; and, briefly, in the "Bibliothèque de 1'Ecole des chartes", XXXII, 1871, pp.255f.]
